Objective

This is a project visualizing cafe sales data. In order to prepare for customers needs and efficient management, data science will work in a significant way. For example, if some particular days sales is low, we can reduce material purchase or lessen workers. Not only with this data but by many other data, we can make clear and efficient decision by visualizing data, making prediction model, and etc.

Analysis process

1. Loading Excel Data using readxl package

In this section, we load the Excel data that contains information on cafe sales, including order IDs, order dates, categories, items, and prices from September 13, 2017, to December 25, 2020.

5. Data Processing

Sales Quantity

We calculate the number of sales for each item.
sales_tr = data.frame(table(sales$item))
head(sales_tr)
##              Var1 Freq
## 1        Affogato  911
## 2       Americano 4540
## 3           Bagel  401
## 4 Black Tea Latte 1120
## 5   Blue Lemonade  878
## 6      Cafe Latte 4587

Item Price

We extract unique item names and their corresponding prices.
sales_item = subset.data.frame(sales, select = c("item", "price"))
sales_item = unique(sales_item)
head(sales_item)
## # A tibble: 6  2
##   item              price

## 3 Chocolate Latte    4500
## 4 Oreo Shake         5500

Table of Item, Price, Sales Quantity

We merge the quantity data with the item price data.
item_list = merge(sales_tr, sales_item, by.x = "Var1", by.y = "item")
head(item_list)
##              Var1 Freq price
## 1        Affogato  911  5500
## 2       Americano 4540  4000
## 3           Bagel  401  3500
## 4 Black Tea Latte 1120  4500
## 5   Blue Lemonade  878  4500
## 6      Cafe Latte 4587  4000

Calculation of Sales Revenue

We calculate the sales revenue by multiplying the sales quantity with the price of each item.
item_list$amount = item_list$Freq * item_list$price
sum(item_list$amount)
## [1] 298975500

Item sold by Season

We categorize the data by seasons
sales$month = months(sales$order_date)

for(i in 1:nrow(sales)){
  if(sales$month[i] == "December" | sales$month[i] == "January" | sales$month[i] == "February")
    {sales$season[i] = "Winter"} 
  else if(sales$month[i] == "March" | sales$month[i] == "April" | sales$month[i] == "May")
    {sales$season[i] = "Spring"} 
  else if(sales$month[i] == "June" | sales$month[i] == "July" | sales$month[i] == "August")
  {sales$season[i] = "Summer"} 
  else {sales$season[i] = "Fall"}}

table(sales$season)
## 
##   Fall Spring Summer Winter 
##  24354  10436  13643  13977

7. Visualization

We will visualize the data using ggplot2

Sales Status Chart

- Visualizing Sales by Category -

We will plot the total sales for each category.
chart1 = data.frame(table(target$category))
ggplot(chart1) + aes(x = Var1, y = Freq) + 
  geom_col(fill = "#4682B4") + 
  labs(x = "Category", y = "Sales", title = "Sales by category") + theme_linedraw() + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 20L, face = "bold", hjust = 0.5), 
                           axis.title.y = element_text(size = 12L, face = "bold"),
                           axis.title.x = element_text(size = 12L, face = "bold"),
                           axis.text.y = element_text(face = "bold"), 
                           axis.text.x = element_text(face = "bold"))

- Visualizing Sales by Month -

We will visualize monthly sales for the years 2018,2019, and 2020.
# Create Year, Month Column
chart2 = target
chart2$date_ym = format(chart2$order_date, "%Y-%m")

chart2 = data.frame(table(chart2$date_ym))
chart2$Var1 <- as.Date(paste0(chart2$Var1, "-01"), format = "%Y-%m-%d")
chart2_18 <- chart2 %>% filter(format(Var1, "%Y") == "2018")

# Sales by month on 2018
ggplot(chart2_18, aes(x = Var1, y = Freq, group = 1)) + 
  geom_line(size = 1, color = "#000000") + 
  geom_point(color = "#173F5F") +
  geom_text(aes(label = Freq), nudge_y = 100) +
  labs(title = "2018 Sales by Month") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 20L,
                                  face = "bold",
                                  hjust = 0.5),
        axis.title.y = element_text(size = 8L, face = "bold"),
        axis.title.x = element_text(size = 8L, face = "bold"),
        axis.text.y = element_text(size = 8L, face = "bold"),
        axis.text.x = element_text(size = 8L, face = "bold"))

- Visualizing Sales by Day -

We visualize sales distribution across different days of the week.
chart3 = target
chart3$weekday = weekdays(sales$order_date)
chart3 = data.frame(table(chart3$weekday))

# Rate calculation
chart3$por = chart3$Freq / sum(chart3$Freq) * 100

# Visualization
ggplot(chart3, aes(x ="", y = por, fill = Var1)) + geom_col() +
  labs(title = "Sales percentage by Day_column", x = "", y = "Percentage", fill = "Day") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 20L,
                                  face = "bold",
                                  hjust = 0.5),
        axis.title.y = element_text(size = 8L, face = "bold"),
        axis.title.x = element_text(size = 8L, face = "bold"),
        axis.text.y = element_text(size = 8L, face = "bold"),
        axis.text.x = element_text(size = 8L, face = "bold"))

# Pi Chart Visualization
ggplot(chart3, aes(x ="", y = por, fill = Var1)) +
  labs(title = "Sales percentage by Day_Pi Chart", x = "", y = "Percentage", fill = "Day") +
  geom_col() + coord_polar(theta = "y") +
  geom_text(color = "white",
            aes(label = paste0(Var1, "\n", round(por, 2), "%")),
            position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5)) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#000000", "#222222", "#444444", "#666666", "#888888", "#999999")) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 20L,
                                  face = "bold",
                                  hjust = 0.5),
        axis.title.y = element_text(size = 8L, face = "bold"),
        axis.title.x = element_text(size = 8L, face = "bold"),
        axis.text.y = element_text(size = 8L, face = "bold"),
        axis.text.x = element_text(size = 8L, face = "bold"))
